Dataset¶

The goal of this project is to predict whether a customer makes a sale based on their activity and its context on a shopping website. The main methods used to accomplish this will be Principal Component Analysis, Logistic Regression, & an Artificial Neural Network.

The data set comes from the "Online Shoppers Purchasing Intention Dataset" found on the UC Irvine Machine Learning Repository.

The link is here: https://archive.ics.uci.edu/dataset/468/online+shoppers+purchasing+intention+dat

And the original publication is here: https://www.semanticscholar.org/paper/Real-time-prediction-of-online-shoppers%E2%80%99-purchasing-Sakar-Polat/747e098f85ca2d20afd6313b11242c0c427e6fb3 (credit to authors C.O. Sakar, S. Polat, M Katricioglu, & Y. Kastro)aset

We have a large dataset gathered from an Excel file with over 12000 entries, and 18 features.

From the source, 'Revenue', is the target variable and tells whether there is a sale or not.

  • The first 6 categories relate to types of pages visited and time spent on each page.

  • The next three, 'BounceRates', 'ExitRates', 'PageValues', measure certain ways customer interact with pages.

  • The rest are pretty much self-explanatory, and largely deal with date & the customer's locality.

Principal Component Analysis- Exploration & Dimensionality Reduction¶

In [7]:
pca = PCA()
pca.fit(df[numerical_features])

explained_variance_ratio = pca.explained_variance_ratio_
print("Explained Variance Ratio:", explained_variance_ratio)

cumulative_variance_ratio = np.cumsum(explained_variance_ratio)
print("Cumulative Explained Variance Ratio:", cumulative_variance_ratio)

num_components = np.argmax(cumulative_variance_ratio >= 0.95) + 1
print("Number of components to keep:", num_components)

pca = PCA(n_components=num_components)
pca_features = pca.fit_transform(df[numerical_features])

pca_columns = [f"PC{i}" for i in range(1, num_components + 1)]
df_pca = pd.DataFrame(data=pca_features, columns=pca_columns)
df = pd.concat([df, df_pca], axis=1)

df.drop(numerical_features, axis=1, inplace=True)

Explained Variance Ratio: [0.24345442 0.12039984 0.10000861 0.0770045  0.07214249 0.06914043
 0.06785531 0.06531362 0.06133242 0.05382567 0.03009925 0.02511474
 0.00877426 0.00553445]
Cumulative Explained Variance Ratio: [0.24345442 0.36385425 0.46386287 0.54086736 0.61300985 0.68215029
 0.7500056  0.81531921 0.87665164 0.9304773  0.96057655 0.98569129
 0.99446555 1.        ]
Number of components to keep: 11

This code is showing us that 11 principal components are going to be used, and the rest should be dropped. The Explained Variance Ratio shows how significant each component is- the first once accounts for about 24% of variation in the data, so its pretty significant. And looking at the cumulative, one sees that by the time we reach 11, we're able to account for about 96% of variance.

This accomplishes dimensionality reduction, which helps us interpret and visualize our results more clearly. We chose a 95% cutoff to avoid a large amount of information loss, while still reaping some benefits of the analysis.

This visualization helps make the above easier to understand, where there's diminishing returns as each component is added- shown by the green bars, and where there's a good amount of exaplined variance- shown by the yellow line.

This visualization shows how our original variables factored into our new principal components. This provides exploration as it gives even more insight into the effect of our variables than our previous heatmap did. The first component is made up of those first six features that we discussed earlier, and which were confirmed by the authors of the dataset to measure similar activity. Also, one sees that in each component, BounceRates, ExitRates, and PageValues, often operate together (although PageValues is often in the inverse direction), which again was similarly grouped. Overall it's encouraging to see that the groupings by the authors and our exploratory analysis agree with the PCA.

K-Fold Cross- Validation

In [26]:
k_folds = 5
kfold = StratifiedKFold(n_splits=k_folds, shuffle=True, random_state=42)

train_accuracies = []
test_accuracies = []

for train_indices, test_indices in kfold.split(X, y):

    X_train, X_test = X[train_indices], X[test_indices]
    y_train, y_test = y[train_indices], y[test_indices]
    
    model = Sequential()
    model.add(Dense(64, input_dim=X_train.shape[1], activation='relu'))
    model.add(Dense(32, activation='relu'))
    model.add(Dense(1, activation='sigmoid'))

    model.compile(loss='binary_crossentropy', optimizer='adam', metrics=['accuracy'])

    model.fit(X_train, y_train, epochs=10, batch_size=32, verbose=0)

    train_loss, train_accuracy = model.evaluate(X_train, y_train, verbose=0)
    train_accuracies.append(train_accuracy)

    test_loss, test_accuracy = model.evaluate(X_test, y_test, verbose=0)
    test_accuracies.append(test_accuracy)

print("Mean Train Accuracy:", np.mean(train_accuracies))
print("Standard Deviation Train Accuracy:", np.std(train_accuracies))

Mean Train Accuracy: 0.8790000081062317
Standard Deviation Train Accuracy: 0.0039051432453650987

We use k-fold cross validation to evaluate our model on different subsets. It confirmed our previous finddings, where Accuracy was pretty high, and variation was pretty low. All good things.

This is a good sign that, along with our other findings, out ANN model is superior as a prediction tool.

Conclusion¶

  • Dataset is of high quality and gave us an easy time at creating effective models.

  • Both the Logistic Regression Model and ANN model posted accuracy rates +90%, while a marginal amount of false positives suggested room for improvement

  • The visualizations we had served as a good indicator that our models were NOT overfitted, or at least, only slightly overfitted.

  • These indications suggest that using Principal Component Analysis was a correct decision as it likely reduced overall noise.

  • For the future, If I wanted to redo the project, I would want to play around with choosing a different amount of principal components and finding the effect on results, I would want to see how adjusting parameters would effect the strength of our Logistic Regression model, and see if we could work with more complexity in our ANN model.
